scrot(1)             command line screen capture utility             scrot(1)

NNAAMMEE
       ssccrroott - command line screen capture utility

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       ssccrroott [_o_p_t_i_o_n_s] [_f_i_l_e]

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       ssccrroott  (SCReenshOT)  is  a  simple command line screen capture utility
       that uses imlib2 to grab and save images. Multiple image  formats  are
       supported through imlib2's dynamic saver modules.

       Some features of the ssccrroott:

              •  support to multiple image formats (JPG, PNG, GIF, etc.).

              •  optimization of the screen shots image quality.

              •  capture  a  specific  window  or  a  rectangular area on the
                 screen with the help of switch.

       ssccrroott also can be used to monitor a desktop PC  in  admin  absent  and
       register unwanted activities.

OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       --hh,, ----hheellpp
              Display help output and exit.

       --vv,, ----vveerrssiioonn
              Output version information and exit.

       --aa,, ----aauuttoosseelleecctt
              Non-interactively choose a rectangle of x,y,w,h.

       --bb,, ----bboorrddeerr
              When selecting a window, grab wm border too.

       --cc,, ----ccoouunntt
              Display a countdown when used with delay.

       --dd,, ----ddeellaayy NNUUMM
              Wait NUM seconds before taking a shot.

       --ee,, ----eexxeecc AAPPPP
              Exec APP on the saved image.

       --qq,, ----qquuaalliittyy NNUUMM
              Image  quality (1-100) high value means high size, low compres‐
              sion. Default: 75. (Effect differs  depending  on  _f_i_l_e  format
              chosen).

       --mm,, ----mmuullttiiddiisspp
              For multiple heads, grab shot from each and join them together.

       --ss,, ----sseelleecctt
              Interactively select a window or rectangle with the mouse.  See
              --ll and --ff _o_p_t_i_o_n_s.

       --ll,, ----lliinnee
              Indicates the style of the line when the  --ss  option  is  used.
              See SELECTION STYLE.

       --ff,, ----ffrreeeezzee
              Freeze the screen when the --ss option is used.

       --uu,, ----ffooccuusseedd
              Use the currently focused window.

       --tt,, ----tthhuummbb NNUUMM||GGEEOOMM
              Generate  thumbnail  too. NUM is the percentage of the original
              size for the thumbnail to be. Alternatively, a GEOMetry can  be
              specified, example: 300x200

       --zz,, ----ssiilleenntt
              Prevent beeping.

       --pp,, ----ppooiinntteerr
              Capture the mouse pointer.

       --oo,, ----oovveerrwwrriittee
              By  default ssccrroott does not overwrite the files, use this option
              to allow it.

       --nn,, ----nnoottee
              Draw a text note. See NOTE FORMAT.

SSPPEECCIIAALL SSTTRRIINNGGSS
       Both the ----eexxeecc and filename parameters  can  take  format  specifiers
       that  are  expanded  by ssccrroott when encountered. There are two types of
       format specifier.  Characters preceded by a  '%'  are  interpreted  by
       ssttrrffttiimmee(2).  See man strftime for examples. These _o_p_t_i_o_n_s may be used
       to refer to the current date and time. The second kind are internal to
       ssccrroott and are prefixed by '$' The following specifiers are recognised:

           $a  hostname
           $f  image path/filename (ignored when used in the filename)
           $m  thumb image path/filename (ignored when used in the filename)
           $n  image name (ignored when used in the filename)
           $s  image size (bytes) (ignored when used in the filename)
           $p  image pixel size
           $w  image width
           $h  image height
           $t  image format (ignored when used in the filename)
           $$  print a literal '$'
           \n  print a newline (ignored when used in the filename)

       Example:

           scrot '%Y-%m-%d_$wx$h.png' -e 'mv $f ~/shots/'

       This     would     create     a    _f_i_l_e    called    something    like
       2000-10-30_2560x1024.png and move it to your shots directory.

SSEELLEECCTTIIOONN SSTTYYLLEE
       When using ----sseelleecctt you can  indicate  the  style  of  the  line  with
       ----lliinnee.

       The following specifiers are recognised:

           style=(solid,dash),width=(range 1 to 8)

       The default style is:

           style=solid,width=1

       Example:

           scrot --line style=dash,width=3 --select

NNOOTTEE FFOORRMMAATT
       The following specifiers are recognised for the option ----nnoottee:

           -f 'FontName/size'
           -t 'text'
           -x position (optional)
           -y position (optional)
           -c color(RGBA) (optional)
           -a angle (optional)

       Example:

           scrot --note "-f '/usr/share/fonts/TTF/DroidSans-Bold/40' -x 10 -y 20 -c 255,0,0,255 -t 'Hi'"

AAUUTTHHOORR
       ssccrroott  was  originally  developed by Tom Gilbert under MIT-advertising
       license and is maintained by some people.

       Currently,  source  code  and  newer   versions   are   available   at
       https://github.com/resurrecting-open-source-projects/ssccrroott

